sentences: Václav Vačkář (born August 12, 1881, Died on February 4th 1954) was a Czech composer and conductor of the late romantic era.

In 1952 he wrote the book “Instrumentace Symfonického Orchestru a Hudby Dechové” (Instrumentation for the Symphony Orchestra and Wind Music) with his aforementioned son Dalibor Cyril Vačkář which is still taught in Czech conservatories.
Vačkář received military training in Przemyśl, Poland from 1895-1898 during which he began learning about music through a military program.
Václav Vačkář (born August 12, 1881, Died on February 4th 1954) was a Czech composer and conductor of the late romantic era.
He is well known for his marches especially for his March “Šohaj” which is well known in his native Czechia.
